China zhutshun@mail.sysu.edu.cn In recent decades, N-heterocyclic carbenes (NHCs) have emerged as a versatile and powerful group of organocata- lysts for asymmetric reactions.1 These catalysts have unique reaction modes that permit the development of highly se- lective and effective reactions that have multiple synthetic applications in a wide variety of organic transformations. To  the  best  of  our  knowledge,  the  very  first  carbene- catalyzed  asymmetric  reaction  dates  back  to  1966,  when Sheehan and Hunneman reported a benzoin condensation reaction catalyzed by the chiral thiazolium NHC catalyst C1 (Scheme 1a).2 Despite its low efficiency in terms of both the yield and enantioselectivity, this reaction is significant for opening  the  door  to  asymmetric  NHC  catalysis.  In  1996, Enders  and  co-workers  reported  the  first  NHC-catalyzed Received: 31.12.2019 Accepted after revision: 18.01.2020 Published online: 03.02.2020 DOI: 10.1055/s-0039-1690814; Art ID: st-2019-p0707-sp

Abstract  In recent decades, organocatalysis by N-heterocyclic carben- es (NHCs) has emerged as a versatile and powerful method in organic synthesis. As a result of the power of NHC organocatalysis to produce cyclic  compounds,  polysubstituted  benzenes,  which  are  among  the most important cyclic compounds in organic chemistry, can be synthe- sized efficiently and selectively. This article briefly summarizes the his- tory  of  NHC  organocatalysis,  including  recent  developments  in  ben- in zene-formation  methods,  and  highlights  our  atroposelective arene formation by carbene-catalyzed formal [4+2] cyclo- additions. We expect that more NHC-catalyzed methods for the synthe- sis of asymmetric arenes will be developed in the near future, providing shortcuts to syntheses of sophisticated chiral functional molecules with polysubstituted benzene nuclei. Key words  N-heterocyclic  carbene,  arenes,  atroposelectivity,  cyclo- addition, asymmetric catalysis © 2020. Thieme. All rights reserved. He participated in a na- tional student innovation training program and joined Professor Zhu’s  group in 2019. After working as a postdoctoral  scholar with Professor Yonggui Robin Chi at Nanyang Technological Uni- versity in Singapore, Tingshun became a professor of chemistry at Sun  Yat-Sen University in 2018. In 2004, Glorius and Bode and their respective co-work- ers  reported  pioneering  works  in  homoenolate  chemistry with  NHC  organocatalysis.4  With  the  sterically  hindered imidazolium NHC catalyst C3, the umpolung activation of a carbonyl  carbon  was  extended  to  the  -carbon  via  a  ho- moenolate  intermediate.  Subsequent  reaction  with  active aldehydes  gave  -butyrolactones  3  in  good  yields  with moderate  diastereoselectivities  (Scheme  2a).  Such  remote umpolung activation modes also permit other effective cy- clization reactions.5 In 2010, Studer and co-workers devel- oped an oxidative activation mode in which a homoenolate intermediate was further transformed into an unsaturated acyl azolium intermediate, and the umpolung activation of the  -carbon  was  restored  to  a  normal  activation  mode through  a  second  umpolung  pathway.6  With  catalyst  C4, cinnamaldehyde reacted efficiently with pentane-2,4-dione to give lactone 4 in excellent yield (Scheme 2b). Acyl azoli- um  chemistry  with  NHC  organocatalysis  was  then  further developed  by  other  researchers.  Besides  the -carbon,  the carbonyl carbon and the -, -, and -carbons of aldehydes have been successfully activated in  various  practical reac- tions.7 It is also worth noting that the catalyst-regeneration process of an NHC can be efficiently achieved by intramo- lecular  nucleophilic  substitution  of  an  acyl  azolium  inter- Scheme 1   Early examples of asymmetric NHC organocatalysis Scheme 2   The development of the remote activation mode: homoenolate chemistry and oxidative acyl azolium chemistry in NHC organocatalysis

As a result, the intrinsic features of NHC organoca- talysis permit the preparation of such cyclized compounds as  lactones,  lactams,  cycloalkanes,  or  cycloalkenes,  among others. Despite  its  powerful  ability  to  construct  cyclic  com- pounds, NHC organocatalysis was not applied to arene-for- mation  reactions  for  several  years.  This  might  have  been partially due to the misconception that syntheses of arenes were already well developed when, in fact, methods for the synthesis  of  substituted  arenes  remained  important  and were far from mature. The classic approach relied on step- wise substitutions of preexisting arenes. In the case of poly- substituted  arenes,  however,  this  stepwise  substitution strategy suffered from problems of regioselectivity. Direct- ing  groups  or  protecting  groups  were  usually  needed, which led to laborious synthetic routes. In comparison, the direct  formation  of  arene  cores  by  using  readily  available prefunctionalized substrates can offer shortcuts to the syn- theses of both small molecules and large sophisticated nat- ural products.

In 1948, Reppe and co-workers developed a transition- metal-catalyzed trimerization of acetylene to give benzene (Scheme 3a).8 This work was of considerable significance in relation to the synthesis of arenes. Similar strategies have been  studied  and  further  developed  by  hundreds  of  re- searchers,  and  the  [2+2+2]  cycloaddition  had  remained  a dominant  strategy  for  arene  formation  up  to  the  present day.  However,  the  enantioselectivity  of  this  method  re- mained  unexplored  for  several  decades  until  1994,  when Mori and co-workers developed the first asymmetric arene- formation  reaction  through  a  Ni-catalyzed  desymmetric [2+2+2]  annulation  with  the  chiral  phosphine  ligand  (S)- MOP (Scheme 3d).9 In 1998, Starý and co-workers reported a  cobalt-catalyzed  intramolecular  [2+2+2]  cycloisomeriza- tion of triynes to give polysubstituted benzenes with helical chirality.10a  Later  in  2004,  Shibata  and  others  successfully used this strategy to build atropisomeric arenes with excel- lent stereoselectivities (Scheme 3e).10b R 3 41–87% yield 3:1 to 5:1 dr . l a i r e t a m d e t h g i r y p o C

A  second  group  of  arene-formation  methods  involved six-membered-ring  pericyclic  reactions  ([4+2]  cycloaddi- tion, 6-electrocyclization, etc.) with successive aromatiza- tion. Because of such advantages as high efficiency, simple reaction conditions (normally heating), and excellent func- tional-group tolerance, this strategy has a wide range of ap- plications in the synthesis of complex molecules. For exam- ple, the Li group and others have used this strategy in effi- cient total syntheses of several natural products including daphenylline,11b  clostrubin,11c  and  rubriflordilactone  B11d (Scheme  3f).  Another  type  of  arene-formation  method  re- lies on an anionic cyclization (Michael reaction, Dieckmann condensation,  aldol  condensation)  and  aromatization  pro- cesses  (elimination,  oxidation,  etc.).  This  strategy  possibly dates back to 1978, and is represented by the Hauser–Kraus annulation12 (Scheme 3b) and the Staunton–Weinreb annu- lation  (Scheme  3c).13  In  recent  decades,  dozens  of  elegant syntheses  of  sophisticated  natural  products  by  using  this strategy  have  been  reported.14  However,  no  asymmetric versions of this strategy were reported. Recently, research- ers have attempted to use organocatalysts to control anion- ic cyclization processes, increasing the power of this strate- gy (Scheme 3g). Among these, NHC-organocatalyzed arene formation is one of the most remarkable methods.

Chi,  Zhu,  and  co-workers  reported  the  first  NHC-or- ganocatalyzed  arene-formation  reactions  in  2013.15  With the imidazolium NHC catalyst C3, enals 17 and enones 18 smoothly  underwent  a  formal  [3+3]  cycloaddition  to  give the 1,2,3,5-tetrasubstituted benzenes 19 in good yields and with  excellent  regioselectivities  (Scheme  4a).  In  2015,  the researchers developed a second example of such a reaction, involving remote activation of the -carbon of the unsatu- rated aldehyde.16 By a simple change in substrate 20, a con- trollable formal [4+2] or [5+4] annulation gave either poly- substituted  benzenes  22  or  methylenebenzofuranones  23 in moderate to good yields and with excellent regioselectiv- ities  (Scheme  4b). There  has  been  recent  progress  in  asymmetric  arene- formation  methods  using  chiral  organocatalysts.  Since 2014, Sparr and co-workers have established several atro- poselective  arene-formation  methods  involving  chiral- intramolecular  aldol  condensations.18 amine-catalyzed  From the elaborately designed unsaturated (Z)-enal 26, the atropisomeric  biaryl  compound  27  was  conveniently  ob- tained  in  good  yield  with  excellent  enantioselectivity (Scheme 5a).18a In 2015, Lupton and co-workers reported an NHC-catalyzed  intramolecular  rearrangement  reaction  for the synthesis of polysubstituted benzaldehydes.19 The cas- cade reaction is elegant and efficient, but shows relatively poor enantioselectivity (Scheme 5b). Inspired by the remarkable features of arene-formation reactions for the efficient synthesis of polysubstituted ben- zene compounds, we became interested in developing novel catalyst-controlled  asymmetric  arene-formation  methods. Learning from the powerful ability of NHC organocatalysts to form cyclic compounds, we surmised that such catalysts might be perfect candidates for such reactions. Initially, we attempted  react  the  -(o-nitroaryl)  ketone  39a  with  enal 38a.23 We reasoned that the nitro group might activate the -position  of  the  ketone  and  provide  sufficient  steric  hin- derance to maintain atropisomerism in product 40a. Fortu- nately,  an  initial  attempt  with  C10  as  the  NHC  catalyst, Cs2CO3 as the base, and THF as the solvent gave the desired product 40a in only about 3% yield. After very careful opti- mization of the conditions, we found the effects of the base and solvent were critical. A strong base led to an intramo- lecular  cyclization  side-reaction  of  the  aldehyde  38a, whereas  a  weak  base  hardly  initiated  the  main  reaction, due to an unfavorable deprotonation of ketone 39a. The op- timized conditions involved DABCO, a relatively weak base, and  a  2:1  (v/v)  mixture  of  NMP  and  tBuOH  as  solvent (Scheme 6).

The  proposed  mechanism  for  the  reaction  is  shown  in Scheme 7. The reaction is initiated by the oxidative conver- sion of 38a into the chiral NHC catalyst-attached acyl azoli- um intermediate I. Subsequently, intermediate I undergoes a stereoselective 1,6-addition with 39a (probably in its enol or enolate form). Under the control of the chiral indane arm of the NHC catalyst, a re-face approach should be favored. Intermediate II, generated by 1,6-addition, then undergoes a  cascade  intramolecular  aldol  reaction/lactone  formation to give intermediate IV, with regeneration of the NHC cata- lyst. On completion of the thermodynamically favored ex- peditious decarboxylation/oxidative aromatization, the at- ropisomeric  product  40a  is  eventually  obtained  through  a central-to-axial chirality conversion. With the optimal reaction conditions in hand (Scheme 6), we further examined the generality of the reaction. Tak- ing the phenyl ketone 39a as a standard substrate, we inves- tigated the reactions of various unsaturated aldehyde sub- strates 38 bearing diverse substituents on the - and -car- bons. To our delight, the reaction accommodated a variety of  substituents,  including  electron-withdrawing  or  elec- tron-donating  groups  in  o-,  m-,  or  p-positions,  giving  the Scheme 6   Optimized reaction conditions Oxidant B (350 mol%) DABCO (50 mol%) NMP–tBuOH = 2:1(v/v) 60 °C . l a i r e t a m d e t h g i r y p o C

corresponding  arenes  40a–n  in  moderate  to  good  yields (35–70%)  and  with  excellent  enantioselectivities  (90–98% ee)  (Scheme  8).  The  absolute  stereochemistry  of  40d  was determined by single-crystal X-ray diffraction analysis, and the compound was shown to have an R configuration.

Next, the enal 38a was used as a model reactant and its reactions  with  various  ketones  39  were  examined.  Com- pounds  39  in  which  the  methyl  group  in  39a  (R3)  was  re- placed  by  various  (het)arenes  containing  electron-with- drawing or electron-donating substituents in the m- or p- positions were all suitable reactants, giving the desired at- ropisomeric  arenes  40o–u  in  excellent  yields  (generally >90%)  and  with  excellent  enantioselectivities  (generally >90%  ee)  .  Increasing  the  electron  deficiency  of  the  aryl group  in  ketone  39  benefited  the  reaction  yields  remark- ably (40v–y). Replacement of the nitro group by other elec- tron-withdrawing groups including –CN (40z), –CF3 (40z1), –Br (40z2), or –POPh2 groups (40z3) was found to be well tolerated, and the corresponding atropisomeric arene prod- ucts were obtained with high enantioselectivities (90–95% ee). In some reactions with low yields, such as that toward 40z3, rescreening of the reaction conditions improved the yield  to  an  acceptable  level.  It  is  also  worth  noting  that switching the phenyl rings in substrates 38 (R2) and 39 (R3), with  the  same  reaction  procedure  and  catalyst,  gave  both enantiomers  of  the  atropisomeric  product  40z4  and  ent- 40z4 in good yields and with excellent enantiomeric excess. Because of the steric similarity of R2 and R3, such products are  very  difficult  to  obtain  in  good  enantioselectivities  by conventional arene-substitution strategies. Synlett 2020, 31, A–H To demonstrate the synthetic potential of our reaction, we prepared several chiral ligands and organocatalysts by direct  transformations  of  its  chiral  products  (Scheme  9). The atropisomeric aniline 41 was conveniently prepared in good yield through reduction of 40a with iron powder. Acy- lation  of  aniline  41  with  oxalyl  chloride  gave  42,  a  chiral version  of  Ma’s  organometallic  ligand,  whereas  acylation with  3,5-bis(trifluoromethyl)phenyl  isocyanate  or  isothio- cyanate gave the urea organocatalyst 44 or the thiourea or- ganocatalyst 45, respectively, all with remarkable enantio- selectivities  (97–99.9%  ee).  Moreover,  simple  reduction  of product  40z3  with  HSiCl3  gave  43,  a  chiral  version  of Buchwald’s  X-Phos-type  phosphine  ligand,  in  quantitative yield.  Furthermore,  the  chiral  carbonyl  organocatalyst  46 was obtained in moderate yield by reduction of product 40z with DIBAL-H. In all these transformations, the optical puri- ties of the products were maintained or even enhanced as a result of crystallization processes.

Last, but not least, we made an initial attempt to achieve another  challenging  target:  an  electrochemical  method  to realize  NHC  oxidative  organocatalysis.  Quinone  oxidant  B has  been  widely  used  since  Studer’s  work  in  2010  (see Scheme 2b). However, its high molecular weight and need for  an  equivalent  loading  result  in  a  decrease  in  the  atom economy of the reaction. The use of a greener oxidant such as air or electrochemical oxidation to realize oxidative NHC- organocatalyzed  reactions  should  result  in  a  marked  in- crease  in  their  potential  for  use  in  industrial  applications. The ability of the optimized solvent NMP to dissolve most electrolytes and its widespread used in lithium-ion battery . l a i r e t a m d e t h g i r y p o C manufacture suggested to us the idea of an electrochemical oxidation  based  on  our  reaction.  For  products  40t,  40w, 40y, and 40z1 as examples, a brief screening of the reaction conditions gave acceptable results (Scheme 10a). However, all yields showed obvious decreases in comparison to those obtained  by  chemical  oxidation.  This  might  be  partially because  quinone  B  is  not  a  very  suitable  redox  catalyst  in our reactions. In conclusion, we have briefly overviewed the history of NHC-organocatalyzed  asymmetric  cyclization  and  arene- formation methods, and have highlighted the importance of the  asymmetric-arene-formation  strategy  and  introduced the  remarkable  potential  of  NHC-catalyzed  asymmetric ent-40z4 76% yield –95% ee . l a i r e t a m d e t h g i r y p o C
